article.headline: Zolman scores 23 points for Lady Vols
article.linkText: No reaching Summitt: Lady Vols beat Kentucky
article.story:
LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Former Tennessee assistant Mickie DeMoss
gave her old boss Pat Summitt a tough test before Kentucky faltered
down the stretch.

Shanna Zolman sank a key 3-pointer with 1:06 left and scored 23
points to lead the top-ranked Lady Vols to an 81-72 win over
Kentucky and DeMoss, who took over the Wildcats last spring after
18 seasons in Knoxville.

Shyra Ely added 22 for Tennessee (17-1, 6-0 Southeastern
Conference), which won its 10th straight game.

Each Tennessee starter hugged DeMoss during pregame
introductions, but DeMoss forgot her emotions after that.

"Once the game began, the focus was on winning the game,"
DeMoss said.

Sara Potts scored a career-high 29 points to lead Kentucky
(9-10, 1-5), which lost to Tennessee for the 23rd consecutive time,
but trailed only 72-67 with two minutes left.

The Wildcats had a chance to get closer, but LaToya Davis
intercepted a pass and got fouled at the other end. Zolman sank a
3-pointer from the corner 20 seconds later to put the Lady Vols up
by eight.

DeMoss figured Zolman would hit the shot -- she used to help with
Zolman with her shooting mechanics.

"It surprises me when she misses," DeMoss said.

Tennessee went 6-for-8 from the free throw line in the final
minute to seal the victory, its first without point guard Loree
Moore. Moore sustained a season-ending knee injury in Tennessee's
win at Duke on Saturday.

Summitt and DeMoss, still close friends, briefly embraced at
midcourt as the game ended, neither wearing a smile. Summitt said
she tried not to think about their relationship as she prepared for
the game.

"Mickie is one of my dearest friends. It was Kentucky and
Tennessee and we just wanted to figure out a way for Tennessee to
execute and be better," Summitt said. "I'm that type of a
competitor and I'm sure Mickie felt the same way."

The Wildcats lost for the sixth time in eight games, but DeMoss
was upbeat about her team's performance.

"This proves that we can do it," she said. "It proves to me
we can play with anybody in the country."

Despite four early turnovers, the Wildcats trailed 9-7 six
minutes into the game. Danyelle Payne's jumper with 7:54 left in
the opening half put the Wildcats up 20-19, their first lead.

The Lady Vols retook the lead and built it to 10, but the
Wildcats finished the half with an 8-2 burst and trailed only 36-32
at the break.

The Lady Vols said DeMoss' intimate knowledge of the program
made the game competitive.

"She knows Coach (Summitt) better than anybody," said Zolman.
"She knows a lot of her tendencies and she taught that to her
team. She knows our personnel and some of our weaknesses and she
brought those out tonight."

Tennessee hit six of its first 10 shots after halftime to
restore the double-digit lead.

Potts' 3-pointer from the top of the key with 11:59 left ended a
3 1/2-minute Kentucky scoring drought and trimmed the Wildcats'
deficit to 54-43.

"She played like an All-American tonight," DeMoss said of
Potts.

Potts sank 11 of 25 shots, including 5-of-12 from 3-point range,
and also grabbed a game-high nine rebounds.

"Everyone knew they had to step up for this game and that's
what we all did," Potts said.

Kentucky mounted a 9-2 spurt following a basket by Sidney
Spencer. Angela Phillips' pull-up jumper with 9:45 remaining drew
the Wildcats to 58-52.

The lead bulged to 12 before back-to-back jumpers by Shambrica
Jones cut the Wildcats' deficit to 68-63 with five minutes left.
Jones, who scored 14, left the game two minutes later with an
apparent knee injury.

Kentucky fell to 0-14 all-time against the No. 1 team, including
seven losses to the Lady Vols.

The game drew 8,429 fans, the second largest crowd for a women's
game at Memorial Coliseum.
